Let $ h(x) $ be a polynomial with leading coefficient $ 1 $, whose roots are $ 1/(p^2+1), 1/(q^2+1), 1/(r^2+1) $, where $ p, q, $ and $ r $ are the roots of $ f(x) = x^3 + ax^2 + bx + c $. Provided that $ a, b, $ and $ c $ are positive integers such that $ a < b < c $, find $ h(1) $ in terms of $ a, b, $ and $ c $.
$ \textbf{(A)} $ 1
$ \textbf{(B)} \frac{1}{c}
$ \textbf{(C)} \frac{c^2}{a+b+c}
$ \textbf{(D)} \frac{a+b+c}{c^2}
$ \textbf{(E)} \frac{1 + a + b + c}{c} $
